  "doc_id": "8384",
  "text": "As SHM is a mostly random process, the benefit of SHM to affinity maturation is tempered by the inevitable generation of GC B cell clones that express self-reactive BCRs. In contrast to tolerance mechanisms that control early B cell development, the means by which selfreactive GC B cells are eliminated is poorly understood. The development of an experimental system in which a transgenic BCR gains cross-reactivity to a self-antigen following SHM has shed new light on the factors that regulate negative selection [CITATION_1] . It was found that self-reactive GC B cells can be successfully cleared when self-antigen is expressed ubiquitously or near to the GC microenvironment. By contrast, GC B cells that are reactive to rare or tissue-specific antigens can escape clearance and are positively selected. The exact mechanism behind these divergent outcomes is yet to be determined.",
